^-{          Effective Overcalls          }
^-|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Knowing what to do when your right-hand opponent (RHO) opens is crucial. On 50% of the deals you play, the player who opens the bidding is your opponent. When that opponent is your RHO, the player in the hot seat is you. When your side opens the bidding, high card points (HCP) play a very significant role in your decision making. But things are very different when the enemy bids first. When your RHO opens, HCP are no longer the key. Level, distribution. Vulnerability and suit quality, as well as your holding in RHO's suit, are much more important.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

In this lesson I will discuss:
' Why you should be super-aggressive when your RHO opens 1@C
' When to pass a strong hand
' Very flexible takeout doubles
' 1-level overcalls ' all you need there is a reason
' 1NT overcalls ' very, very descriptive bids
' 2-level overcalls ' a 6-card suit is the norm
' 2-suited overcalls ' why some are better than others
' Jump overcalls ' how aggressive should you be|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

The only overcall that is defined by high card points is 1NT. Therefore, many players are uncertain about the requirements for overcalls and takeout doubles. The material presented here will definitely help you clarify these issues. Do all bridge experts agree with all of my suggestions? Of course not. However, regardless of your bridge level, the contents of this presentation will be very helpful in your future bidding.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

When the opponent opens 1 of minor, you want to be very aggressive. It is ok to make a takeout double without a perfect holding in the other minor because your partner is so likely to respond in a major. Those are the important suits. It's even ok to make a takeout double with 3 or 4 cards in the opponent's minor. You want to get in when you can with a decent hand, and you will never have a cheaper opportunity than when an opponent opens 1 of a minor. Takeout doubles are an excellent flexible action.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


NT||
