qx||st||pn|Marty Bergen,,Partner,|md|4S 6 4 H A 9 D A K Q T 7 5 4 C K 2,,,|sv|b|rh||ah|Hand 25|ah|Bergen's Audio Visual|AH|Effective Overcalls|mb|1s?|lb|*bWhat do you do?^^3s|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|This is a terrific hand. I've got eight tricks in my hand, and the King of clubs doesn't hurt, particularly behind the opening bidder. So all I need for 3NT is for partner to have a spade stopper. Even @SJ10xx|Md|0,0,sjt32,0|at| would stop them from running the suit. If that's all partner has, then they can defeat 3NT if they lead hearts early. |
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|But if your opponents always lead and defend perfectly, neither you nor I are going to win. So, if I can find partner with a spade stopper, I'll take my chances in 3NT. How do I go about achieving that? Many players would do a 'big double' scenario, or would overcall 2@D and hope partner bids no trump. And it's possible that those actions will work out OK.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|But in fact there is a very descriptive, right-to-the-point bid available. It's fair to call this an advanced bid that not all players know about. It's also fair to call this a sexy bid, one that if you learn it, and you and your partner both remember it, and you get the occasion to use it (these hands come up occasionally), you can have your cake and eat it too, and really have a memorable hand.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|So the expert bid here, when they open one of a major, is to jump to 3 of their major, which doesn't mean 'my suit is better than yours' (to the opponents). |
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|What it does mean, when you make this bid in a minor, as we saw earlier, 1@C-3@C or 1@D-3@D should be played as weak jump overcalls -- preempts with length and strength in the opponents' minor. |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|But in a major, where the opponent is promising at least five, then we believe that the right way to play is that this bid says 'partner, I have a long running minor, I have a nice hand, but I don't have a stopper in the opponents' major. If you have a stopper, please bid 3NT; if not, then retreat to 4@C with a normal hand, and I'll announce which minor I have by passing or bidding 4@D.'|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Of course, if you have a terrific hand ' let's say you had a singleton spade and some useful high cards in the other suits, you could control bid or cue bid 4@S to say: 'Hey Marty, I can't bid 3NT like you were hoping, but I don't want to stop in a part score since you're strong and I have a good hand with a key singleton, so let's play in game in your minor, or possibly even slam.'|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Anyway, so much for fantasizing. For now, 3@S is the bid if your partner will understand you.|MB|3S|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Otherwise, you'll have to choose between 2@D and a double. If I were playing with someone where I couldn't bid 3@S, I would settle for a 2@D overcall, hoping I got another chance, and praying that partner would bid no trump with a spade stopper if she had one.|
